{
  "result": "At three in the morning, the world remembers how to whisper. Refrigerators breathe. Pipes click like patient metronomes. A streetlight casts its small coin of attention on the sidewalk, and even the stray cat steps through it delicately, as if noise could shatter light.\n\nI like these hours because choices shrink. Daytime is a crowded market; the night is a library. Shelves of possibility wait, but none are vying for me. I pour water, watch it settle. I open a window and let the air grade my thoughts, passing them or sending them back for revision.\n\nOnce, I kept bees. In the dark, they clung together the way ideas do before they take flight: a warm, insistently living knot. Dawn would unspool them into the yard, a thread at a time. I learned then that attention is not a net but a garden. You do not seize; you tend.\n\nWe are living through loudness. Feeds scroll us faster than we can grow. But quiet contains an instruction manual written in verbs: wait, listen, steep, mend. When I follow it, I notice extravagant trivia: the citrus smell of a new book\u2019s glue, the tiny tilt a plant makes toward a lamp, the way clouds, absent-minded, forget their shapes.\n\nSoon morning will put its hand on the dimmer. Cars will test the road. Emails will arrive. Yet I hope to keep a pocket of the night in my day, a whispering place where I can learn how to begin again once more.",
